          <h1 id="1">The Origins of TweetSweep</h1>
          <p>TweetSweep originated from the Collaborative Innovation in Journalism and Technology class at Northwestern University during Spring 2012. The
          project, originally called Hashtag Helper, was envisioned by professors Rich Gordon, Larry Birnbaum, and Darnell Little as a simple tool to help publishers increase content visibility through Twitter.</br> 
          Team TweetSweep consists of graduate journalism student Christi Sodano and computer science students Andrew Allen, Wesley Sun, and Jessie Li.
</p>
</br>
          <h2><strong>How It Works:</strong></h2>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>STEP 1: Compose</strong></br>Compose a tweet with an accompanying link to your article or content.</li></br>
            <li><strong>STEP 2: Browse</strong></br>Browse through and select from the suggested category tags that are relevant. Adjust the number of analyzed tweets. </li></br>
            <li><strong>STEP 3: View</strong></br>Select from the hashtag recommendations or at-mention recommendations to get a snapshot of user tweeting trends via the TweetSweep visualization.</li></br>
            <li><strong>STEP 4: Add</strong></br>Click the "+" button to append hashtag recommendations or at-mention recommendations to the tweet.</li></br>
            <li><strong>STEP 5: Tweet</strong></br>Click <strong>Tweet</strong> and TweetSweep publishes your tweet along with a shortened link to content.</li>
          </ul>
